Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Estonia. The Estonian authorities have introduced measures in response to the coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic to limit the spread of the virus. You should comply with any additional screening measures put in place by the authorities.
The Estonian authorities are advising against all travel in and out of Estonia. In addition, further temporary border controls will be introduced from 17 March limiting entry to Estonian nationals, those with an Estonian Residence Permit or foreign citizens with family members in Estonia. All those entering will also now be required to complete a health declaration on arrival and self quarantine for 14 days. There are some exceptions to this including diplomats, healthcare workers and those transporting goods and raw materials provided they are asymptomatic.
Travel to and from Estonia’s Western islands has also been limited to residents only and the ferry company Tallinn have suspended the Tallinn-Stockholm route. There are no restrictions for exiting the country.
For information on how to return to the UK from Estonia, see Return to the UK
The Estonian Police and Border Guard will carry out health checks at international border crossing points (land, ports and airports) to identify travellers’ country of departure and check for symptoms of coronavirus.
Check Estonian Health Board Website for up to date information in English about coronavirus in Estonia. If you have symptoms of coronavirus, Estonian Health Board advises calling family physician advisory line on + 372 634 6630 or 1220 if dialing within Estonia.
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
You can find more information about cases in Estonia on the TravelHealthPro website.
